
## Data Flow
Customer risk assessment in banking depends on information coming from multiple source systems. This information needs to be brought together in a structured way before it can support a reliable risk decision.

In this use case, relevant data may come from:
- customer profile data
- ownership and UBO data
- geographical and country risk data
- business activity information
- transaction behaviour data


### Example Data Sources
[Data Source](Corrected.png)

In practice, this information may be collected from a combination of internal systems, customer-provided documents, and external reference sources, such as:

- Customer profile data  
  (e.g. annual audited reports, client websites, external data providers such as Dun & Bradstreet)

- Ownership and UBO data  
  (e.g. ownership structures, KVK records, certified documents for high-risk cases)

- Geographical and country risk data  
  (e.g. country information derived from ownership structures, client presence, and transaction activity)

- Business activity information  
  (e.g. audited financial reports, company disclosures, client website)

- Transaction behaviour data  
  (e.g. internal systems such as Siebel or transaction monitoring systems)
